Regarding to real-time systems consisting of several components, which are
 connected by a network, aspects like failsafe data transmission as soon
 as guaranteed data transmission times are of significant importance.
 An approach to fulfil these requirements is provided by the High Availability
 Seamless Redundancy (hereinafter also referred to as HSR) protocol.
 Redundant data transmission and also the structure of the compounds implemented
 as a ring topology rank as main characteristics of the HSR protocol.
 The main focus of this thesis consists of the modelling of various scenarios
 based on a HSR ring network composed of distinct instances of HSR end devices.
 For this purpose a virtual HSR node is programmed, which implements certain
 rule sets.
 These rule sets apply to the handling of Ethernet frames and the dataflow
 in a HSR ring.
 To achieve guaranteed maximum transmission times, Ethernet frames are prioritiz
ed, which allows the preemption of low prioritized Ethernet frames.
 Concerning this, the IEEE Draft P802.3br / D1.0 
